{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2719"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.08,0.36,0.02,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55544"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2719"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41084"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55544"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45 year old woman is brought to the Emergency Department after her husband became concerned that she was having difficulty walking and appeared confused. These changes became apparent over the last day. Her medical details are provided by her husband. Her medical history includes non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, Grave\u0027s disease and a Roux-en-y gastric bypass four years ago. Her current medications consist of carbimazole, furosemide and atorvastatin. She does not take any over-the-counter medications. She has no allergies, non-smoker and drinks about one glass of wine a night with occasional alcohol free days.\u00a0She eats a normal, varied diet, but reduced quantity because of her bariatric surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her observations are within normal limits and she is afebrile. She is not orientated to time or place and appears slightly drowsy intermittently. She is unable to walk. She has impaired lateral gaze and has nystagmus when looking horizontally. Upward gaze is preserved. Facial sensation is intact bilaterally, and there is no dysarthria. In her upper and lower limbs, her power is intact bilaterally and reflexes are symmetrical and she has no sensory deficits. However she has marked incoordination and ataxia of her upper limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alcohol use","Hyperthyroidism","Roux-en-y bypass","Furosemide","Liver disease (non-alcoholic fatty liver type)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with acute confusion. Combined with the clinical features of ataxia, horizontal nystagmus and ophthalmoplegia,\u00a0\u003Cem\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy\u003C/em\u003E\u00a0(WE) needs to be suspected.\u00a0WE is an acute rapid onset brain syndrome secondary to thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency.\u00a0Thiamine has many roles but primarily acts as a co-enzyme in the Krebs\u0027 cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECauses of thiamine deficiency\u00a0include reduced intake (commonly in alcoholics and extreme dieting), decreased intestinal absorption (\u003Cstrong\u003Egastric bypass\u003C/strong\u003E, gastrointestinal disease), increased consumption (hyperthyroidism, pregnancy), increased depletion (diarrhoea, frusemide use), severe liver disease, and co-existing folate deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol use\u003C/strong\u003E is to not excess (provided they are being honest) and is unlikely to be the main cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E increases the renal excretion of thiamine and while likely contributing, is overall unlikely to be the main cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer Grave\u0027s disease is currently treated with carbimazole and hence she is likely to be euthyroid (or at worst have well controlled \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer \u003Cstrong\u003Efatty liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be severe enough to be the main cause\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe had a roux-en-y gastric bypass four years ago and is notably not using vitamin supplements. The body\u0027s stores of thiamine only last one month and she is likely to be deficient in many vitamins/electrolytes. WE occurs in approximately 1-2% of gastric bypass patients and should be considered for any acute confusional state in a patient with a bypass history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute confusional state + ophthalmoplegia/nystagmus + ataxia --\u003E think Wernicke\u0027s"],"references":["Chang HW, Yang PY, Han T, Meng NH. Wernicke encephalopathy\u00a0concurrent with polyradiculoneuropathy in a young man after bariatric surgery A case report. Medicine. 2019; 98(10).","Nickson, C. Thiamine deficiency. Sydney (NSW): Life in the Fast Lane; 2020 Nov 3 [cited 2021 Aug 3]. Available from: https://litfl.com/thiamine-deficiency/.","Swaminathan A. Wernicke Encephalopathy. REBEL core; 2018 [cited 2021 Aug 3]. Available from: https://rebelem.com/wernicke-encephalopathy/","Ventura A, Mafe MC, Bourguet M, Tornero C. Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy secondary to hyperthyroidism and ingestion of thiaminase-rich products. Neurolog\u00eda. 2013; 28(4): 257-259"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41084"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41084"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T17:07:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T17:08:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2719"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55544"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"h